title: Support increasing batch size
body:
Revive the following contribution: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/45338

**Changes:**
- change the behavior of `data_adapter.DataAdapter` and `data_adapter.DataHandler` to accept batch size that are increasing during training
- add unit test with `keras.utils.Sequence` that increases its batch size from 5 to 10 over the course of 2 epochs
- add unit test which checks correct behavior of `data_adapter.DataAdapter` and `data_adapter.DataHandler`

**Resources:**
- Idea for increasing batch size: https://arxiv.org/abs/1711.00489
- Rasa workaround: https://github.com/RasaHQ/rasa/blob/main/rasa/utils/tensorflow/temp_keras_modules.py#L477
- Rasa BatchSequence which increases batch size over time: https://github.com/RasaHQ/rasa/blob/main/rasa/utils/tensorflow/data_generator.py#L333

title: Fix TypeError positional argument when used conjointly with tfa wrappers
body:
Some wrappers in tensorflow-addons (eg. `MultiOptimizer`) only accept the list of grads/vars as positional arguments, and reduce the remaining arguments into `**kwargs` that will be passed onto the inner optimizer. Applying `LossScalerOptimizer` to them raises the following error:

```
File ".../python3.9/site-packages/keras/mixed_precision/loss_scale_optimizer.py", line 671, in _apply_gradients
    self._optimizer.apply_gradients(

TypeError: apply_gradients() takes 2 positional arguments but 3 were given
```

Which can be easily fixed by transforming `name` into a named argument.
This way is also more consistent with how `keras.optimizer_v2.optimizer_v2.OptimizerV2#minimize` invokes `apply_gradients`.

title: Currently `model.predict` is allowing values NaN and Inf as inputs, which results in strange results as mentioned in the following issue.
body:
Currently `model.predict` is allowing values NaN and Inf as inputs, which results in strange results as mentioned in the following issue. 

Added a check to make sure inputs doesn't contain NaN or Inf (numpy or Tensor). If there is any undesired inputs, then the code will throw a ValueError as shown below. 

`ValueError: Unsupported input data format. Received: inf in input data. Was expecting a numeric data.`

Fixes https://github.com/keras-team/keras/issues/16158

title: fix model.fit() slow with sample_weight
body:
An issue was opened at the tensorflow repository: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/48965
And the related pull request was denied because this needs to be submitted to keras: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/54368
I'm re-submitting it here since it has been 3 weeks and the original author hasn't submitted a pull-request at the keras repo.

This is a small bugfix to improve performance when using `sample_weight` in `model.fit()`. Currently list comprehension is used to check that there are no None is sample_weight. This creates a very noticeable delay in the start of the fitting procedure when comparing a model with vs. without weights added.  The list comprehensions are changed to array operations to improve performance.

title: Fixes https://github.com/keras-team/keras/issues/16023
body:
Fixes https://github.com/keras-team/keras/issues/16023

Saving a model before training or evaluating on some data, will result in bad performance when trained. This happens only when the loss function is `sparse_categorical_crossentropy`. Root-cause of the issue is due to inferring the `accuracy` metric as a `categorical_crossentropy` instead of `sparse_categorical_accuracy`
